  <!-- ═══════════════════════════════════════════════════════
       D. SCIENCE NARRATIVE — bone background
           Licking/cortisol mechanism, two-mat science,
           40-minute window, vagus nerve activation
  ══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════ -->
  <section class="pcm-narrative pcm-section" aria-label="The licking mechanism">
    <div class="pcm-narrative-inner">

      <span class="pcm-narrative-eyebrow pcm-reveal">The mechanism</span>
      <h2 class="pcm-narrative-headline pcm-reveal">
        Using the same mat every day<br>is the problem, not the solution.
      </h2>

      <div class="pcm-narrative-block">

        <div class="pcm-narrative-item pcm-reveal">
          <span class="pcm-narrative-item-title">Licking and the parasympathetic system</span>
          <p class="pcm-narrative-item-body">
            Repetitive licking activates the parasympathetic branch of the autonomic nervous system. It is not a distraction &mdash; it is a physiological downregulation mechanism. The rhythmic oral motor action stimulates the vagus nerve, reducing heart rate and cortisol production before the departure anxiety cycle can establish itself.
          </p>
        </div>

        <div class="pcm-narrative-item pcm-reveal">
          <span class="pcm-narrative-item-title">Vagus nerve activation</span>
          <p class="pcm-narrative-item-body">
            Vagal tone is the nervous system&rsquo;s capacity to return to calm after a stressor. Slow, sustained licking is one of the most reliable vagal stimulation methods available without clinical intervention. The food element is secondary &mdash; the licking motion itself is the mechanism.
          </p>
        </div>

        <div class="pcm-narrative-item pcm-reveal">
          <span class="pcm-narrative-item-title">The 40-minute cortisol window</span>
          <p class="pcm-narrative-item-body">
            Cortisol in separated dogs peaks between 30 and 40 minutes after departure. This is the biological window where anxiety becomes self-reinforcing. Engaging the parasympathetic system before this peak &mdash; not after &mdash; is what prevents the habituation of chronic departure distress.
          </p>
        </div>

        <div class="pcm-narrative-item pcm-reveal">
          <span class="pcm-narrative-item-title">Why two mats, not one</span>
          <p class="pcm-narrative-item-body">
            Neurological engagement degrades with repetition. A dog exposed to the same mat daily habituates to the stimulus &mdash; the reward-anticipation response diminishes, and with it, the depth of parasympathetic activation. Rotating between two mats resets the novelty signal each session, sustaining engagement past the critical cortisol window.
          </p>
        </div>

      </div>

      <blockquote class="pcm-narrative-callout pcm-reveal">
        &ldquo;One mat every day trains the nervous system to ignore it. Two mats, rotated, keep the conditioned response sharp enough to do the work.&rdquo;
      </blockquote>

    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- ═══════════════════════════════════════════════════════
       E. PROTOCOL INTEGRATION — dark background
           How the Calm Mat slots into the PAXA 30-day protocol
  ══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════ -->
  <section class="pcm-protocol pcm-section" aria-label="PAXA 30-day protocol">
    <div class="pcm-protocol-inner">

      <span class="pcm-protocol-eyebrow pcm-reveal">30-day protocol</span>
      <h2 class="pcm-protocol-headline pcm-reveal">
        The mat activates the system.<br>The protocol changes it.
      </h2>
      <p class="pcm-protocol-intro pcm-reveal">
        The PAXA Calm Mat is a physiological tool &mdash; it creates the neurological conditions for calm. On its own, it provides enrichment. Within the PAXA 30-day protocol, it becomes a conditioned cue woven through four structured phases of systematic desensitisation and counter-conditioning.
      </p>

      <div class="pcm-phases pcm-reveal">

        <div class="pcm-phase">
          <span class="pcm-phase-days">Days 1&ndash;7</span>
          <span class="pcm-phase-name">Foundation</span>
          <p class="pcm-phase-desc">Establish baseline calm. Introduce the mat in low-stakes environments. Build the departure-mat association before any threshold work begins.</p>
        </div>

        <div class="pcm-phase">
          <span class="pcm-phase-days">Days 8&ndash;14</span>
          <span class="pcm-phase-name">Desensitisation</span>
          <p class="pcm-phase-desc">Begin systematic exposure to departure cues while the dog remains below threshold. The mat anchors parasympathetic activation during each exposure session.</p>
        </div>

        <div class="pcm-phase">
          <span class="pcm-phase-days">Days 15&ndash;21</span>
          <span class="pcm-phase-name">Incremental Distance</span>
          <p class="pcm-phase-desc">Extend absence duration in measured increments. The mat&rsquo;s conditioned cue grows stronger as the dog learns that departure predicts the most rewarding experience of the day.</p>
        </div>

        <div class="pcm-phase">
          <span class="pcm-phase-days">Days 22&ndash;30</span>
          <span class="pcm-phase-name">Real-World Resilience</span>
          <p class="pcm-phase-desc">Introduce variability &mdash; different departure times, routes, durations. The conditioned response must generalise across contexts for the change to be permanent.</p>
        </div>

      </div>

      <a href="https://paxapet.gumroad.com/l/PAXA-Solo" class="pcm-protocol-cta pcm-reveal" rel="noopener">
        Add the protocol &mdash; PAXA Solo &mdash; &pound;29 &rarr;
      </a>

    </div>
  </section>

